<HEADLINE> Indonesia, China on Way to Semi-Finals in Thomas Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Indonesia and
tied third-placer China both made it to the second round after
their respective victories in the opening group ties at the 20th
Thomas Cup men's badminton world team championships finals here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia trounced the Netherlands 5-0 in two hours and 17
minutes in Group B and China downed Sweden five matches to none in
their Group A tie, both in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese team had two of the games lost on the way to
the opening tie triumph. Chinese Yang Ming teamed with Zhang Jun
to beat their Swedish opponents Jens Olsson and Frederik Bergstrom
15-2, 11-15, 15-3.
</P>
<P>
China's former world No. 1 player Dong Jiong was held to three
games before winning over Daniel Eriksson 15-10, 12-15, 15-10 in
52 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Our players performed better than I had expected. Some of our
younger players were a bit nervous today and after we won the
first three matches, they were too relaxed to concentrate," said
Chinese head coach Li Yongbo.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe he wished to let the match last longer so that he could
get more used to the court for the more important matches ahead,"
the player-turned-coach said when asked about Dong's performance.
</P>
<P>
And in other actions on Saturday, Malaysia defeated South Korea
4-1.
</P>
<P>
The team of Hong Kong, China, was overjoyed after 20-year-old
Kwok Wa Liu upset current world singles champion Petre Rasmussen
18-14, 6-15, 15-10 in the final singles match. This is the first
time in history that a Hong Kong player has ever won a match in
the Thomas Cup Finals, not to say beat a current world champion.
</P>
<P>
However, the team lost to Sweden 4-1.
</P>
<P>
A foot injury obviously hampered Rasmussen's on-court efforts
especially when he tried to save pressing shots from his opponent.
</P>
<P>
"Although the victory meant nothing important to the team
standings, it is indeed a big boost to the player himself and the
whole team," said Chan Chi Choi, head coach of the Hong Kong,
China, team.
</P>
<P>
Tears in eyes, Liu had to calm himself down for a while before
he could be interviewed. "All I could do today was to try my best
and I think the Dane's errors helped me a lot. I tried to take the
initiative step by step and it worked," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I owed my victory to my coaches," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sunday will see further actions in Uber Cup when Indonesia will
play the Netherlands and South Korea face England in Group B while
in Group A, China will take on Japan and Denmark play Hong Kong,
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
