<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Parties Flay Government Nuclear Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Four Indian parties on Saturday
criticized the government's nuclear policy for being "reckless and
adventurous", and urged immediate finish to India's talk of
nuclear weaponization.
</P>
<P>
The four parties, the Communist Party of India (Marxism), the
Communist Party of India (CPI), the Communist Party of India
(Marxism-Leninism) and the Forward Block condemned the
government's nuclear policy in a joint statement issued after a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
They said the declaration by Prime Minister Atal Vajpayee on
his government's decision to develop nuclear weapons was "fraught
with serious consequences".
</P>
<P>
Production of nuclear weaponry was "unwarranted and contrary to
the interests of the country", said the statement. It added:
"There is no direct threat posed by any country against India
which necessitates such a step. "
</P>
<P>
The party leaders urged the government to take steps to restore
relations with its neighbors and to rely upon past policy working
for nuclear disarmament, while safeguarding the nation's security
by not signing treaties like the Non-proliferation Treaty and the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
