<HEADLINE> Iran, Iraq Reach Agreement on Pilgrimage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Iraq have agreed to
exchange pilgrims to the holy Islamic sites in the two countries,
the evening daily Resalat reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy governor of Iran's Kermanshah Province bordering Iraq
was quoted by the paper as saying that the two sides would
exchange 3,000 pilgrims every week under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The official, whose name was not given in the report, did not
say when and where the agreement was signed.
</P>
<P>
Expressing welcome to the agreement, the official said the
first group of Iranian pilgrims would visit the Shiite holy sites
in southern Iraq in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein announced last August to open
the Shiite sites in his country to Iranian pilgrims. In response,
Iran called for talks to reach an agreement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq, former foes which fought for eight years from
1980 to 1988, have stepped up efforts to solve their problems,
including the issues of prisoners of war (POW) and those missing
in actions (MIA).
</P>
<P>
Last month, the two countries swapped 5,584 Iraqi POWs and 319
Iranians, the largest move since 1992, and last week, they started
operations to search MIAs on each other's territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
