<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Demonstrate Against Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 16 (Xinhua) -- About 500 social activists and
volunteers of different organizations in India held a
demonstration just outside the Delhi police headquarters Saturday
against the government's nuclear policy.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators carried placards and shouted slogans such as
"we want breads not bombs, we need homes not tombs."
</P>
<P>
They demanded total elimination of nuclear weapons from the
world and said it is a matter of great shame that "we should
celebrate India's capability to kill millions of people."
</P>
<P>
The also condemned the imposition of sanctions on India by the
United States and other big powers.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, four political parties urged the government
to immediately stop the talk of nuclear weaponization as it would
lead to a harmful nuclear arms race between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued here Saturday, they said the public
declaration by Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee that his
government has decided to go ahead with making and induction of
nuclear weapons was a major policy declaration "fraught with
serious consequences."
</P>
<P>
The statement from the Communist Party of India (Marxism)
(CPI-M), the Communist Party of India (CPI), the Communist Party
of India (Marxism-Leninism) (CPI-ML) and the Forward Block
followed a meeting here between their leaders.
</P>
<P>
Making of nuclear bombs and weaponry at this juncture is
"unwarranted and contrary to the interests of the country," the
statement said, adding that "there is no direct threat posed by
any country against India which necessitates such a step."
</P>
<P>
The ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) has rushed into this
adventurist policy with the political motive of arousing feelings
of chauvinism and jingoism to cover up its own political
difficulties of running a rickety coalition and its failure to
address serious problems facing the country, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The party leaders asked the government to take steps to improve
relations with neighboring countries and rely upon the past policy
of working for nuclear disarmament while safeguarding India's
security interests by not signing treaties like the
non-proliferation treaty and the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Congress party said Saturday that the nuclear
tests carried out by the BJP-led government earlier this week,
while claimed to be for national security, were also for gaining
political mileage for the BJP with a view to capitalizing on them
in the event of mid-term elections.
</P>
<P>
In a background paper prepared for the extended Congress
Working Committee, the Congress said the BJP has demonstrably
started preparing for a possible mid-term polls to come back to
power on its own as it feels that the Vajpayee government might
not last long.
</P>
<P>
The Rashtriya Janata Dal also charged that the BJP-led
government was trying to take political gains out of the nuclear
tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
