<HEADLINE> GCC to Speed Process of Unifying Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The finance ministers of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Saturday agreed to speed the
process of unifying their customs tariff, Kuwait News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministers of Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Oman, Bahrain and
the United Arab Emirates (UAE), which form the GCC, discussed the
issue at their one-day meeting held in Saudi capital Riyadh, but
left the final decision to the next GCC summit scheduled in
December.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Finance Minister Sheikh Ali Salem Al-Sabah was quoted
by the news agency as saying that the GCC members have been
proceeding firmly toward "building a customs wall" and there is
no differences among them in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He said that the GCC commodity classification committee will
finish the discussion of the subject later.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,140 commodities out of 1,289 have been categorized. And
sources close to the meeting said that some members eased their
stances on the classification of the remaining commodities at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
But Saudi Arabia and the UAE have reservations over the
classification of some commodities, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Current customs tariffs of the GCC states vary from 4 percent
to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The goods will be put in three categories, namely goods
exempted from tariffs, basic goods with a tariff of 4 to 8 percent
or 8 to 12 percent, and other goods.
</P>
<P>
Gaps exist in GCC states over the unification of tariff due to
differences in their economic priorities. The disagreement has
blocked a tariff agreement almost since the alliance was formed in
1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
