<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-16 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNC Members Calls for Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National Council
(PNC) members residing in Jordan said in a statement issued
Saturday that the time has come for the Palestinians to see the
Palestinian state that was declared in Tunis in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which was broadcast by the Voice of Palestine,
said it is time for millions of the Palestinian refugees who were
forced to flee 50 years ago to return to their homeland now.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat declared the Palestinian state
in Tunis in 1988 and plans to establish an independent
Palestinian state in May, 1999 on the territories of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip under the Oslo Accords.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has threatened to take counter actions if Arafat
carries out his plan.
</P>
<P>
The statement called on all Arab leaders to answer the
Palestinian call for an Arab summit to deal with the situation the
peace process is facing.
</P>
<P>
It blamed Israel for pushing the peace process into deadlock,
saying that the Israeli government is challenging the the Arab
world and the international legitimate decisions.
</P>
<P>
The PNC continued to support a just and comprehensive peace,
but affirmed that there can be no peace without the return of the
Palestinian refugees to their land and without Jerusalem as the
capital of an independent Palestinian state, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The PNC is the highest governing body in Palestine, consisting
of all members of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and
leaders of various political factions of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
There are about 3.2 to 3.6 million Palestinian refugees and
most of them are living in Jordan and Lebanon now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
