<HEADLINE> Lebanon Reiterates Rejection of Talks on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese House Speaker Nabih Berri
reiterated on Saturday his country's refusal to negotiate with
Israel over its withdrawal offer from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We reaffirm our rejection of any negotiations" with Israel,
Berri told a rally held in Shagra town in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese people should know that whatever Israel has proposed,
including the Lebanon First, conditional withdrawal and what it
said on Friday, are all aimed at escaping international efforts
to achieve a comprehensive peace in the Middle East, he added.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Israel put forward the Lebanon First proposal, which
suggested that its problems with Lebanon be solved first and then
that with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria rejected the proposal, arguing that Israel
was trying to drive a wedge between the two sides. They insisted
that they will negotiate with Israel simultaneously and not make
peace unilaterally with it.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel adopted the United Nations Security Council
Resolution 425, which demands unilateral Israeli withdrawal from
Lebanon. But Israel conditioned its troop pullback on security
arrangements with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which agree to coordinate stances on key
issues, have rejected the offer, insisting that the withdrawal be
unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Berri said all the Israeli offers are aimed at separating
Lebanon and Syria in the peace talks with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants the return of the Golan Heights captured by Israel
in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a so-called security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 to allegedly protect its northern areas from cross-border
attacks by Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese resistance forces have been fighting to drive the
Israeli troops out of Lebanon and the ensuing heavy casualties
suffered by the Israeli troops have sparked public pressure in
Israel on the government to withdraw its troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
