<HEADLINE> S. Leoneans Demonstrate to Back Alleged Arms Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- People in Freetown, capital of
Sierra Leone, Saturday waged a demonstration in the support of
arms supply by a British firm for the restoration of the
country's legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, the British company, Sandline
International, shipped arms and ammunition early this year to
Sierra Leone which was at that time under a United Nations arms
embargo as a measure to punish the military junta.
</P>
<P>
The then ousted Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah,
reportedly contacted British High Commissioner (ambassador) to
Sierra Leone Peter Penfold before the controversial arms deal.
</P>
<P>
Some British parliamentarians have been politicalizing the
deal, saying it was a breach of the U.N. arms sanction.
</P>
<P>
However, the people in Sierra Leone think differently and are
getting angry.
</P>
<P>
To Sierra Leoneans who suffered a lot since last May's
military coup, the west African peacekeeping force had already
done the job in a bid to overthrow the junta, before Sandline.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, the right thing has been done at the end of the day as
the whole world agreed the junta should be removed and the
democratically elected government brought back.
</P>
<P>
They do not understand why anybody should wish it otherwise,
according to a British Broadcasting Corporation report monitored
here.
</P>
<P>
So it is not a surprise the people from all sides of Freetown
demand the return of the British ambassador who is now in London
to answer some questions from the Customs and other departments
which are investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
In what the report described as a "quite remarkable" way, the
demonstrators kept chanting "Peter Penfold, We Love You" and
"Come back, Peter Penfold".
</P>
<P>
Some of them even said they don't want anybody else if the
British government tried to replace him.
</P>
<P>
One of the things the people are asking the government to do
is to grant Peter Penfold honorary citizenship of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The angry people also condemned some of the British
parliamentarians, whose names the report said were completely
unbroadcastable.
</P>
<P>
They believed one of the parliamentarians was the enemy of the
Sierra Leoneans.
</P>
<P>
In Makeni, Bo and other major towns, people were also been out
on the streets to protest the politicalization of the alleged
arms deal, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
