<HEADLINE> Arab League Prepares Nuclear Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) Technical
Committee charged with preparing a draft treaty to render the
Middle East free from weapons of mass destruction, is slated to
meet on Tuesday at its Cairo headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meetings of the ad-hoc technical committee, which
groups 13 Arab states, will embark on phrasing the treaty text,
setting its period of duration as well as the time span needed for
its revision.
</P>
<P>
The draft is "certainly unique" in the sense that it prohibits
all massively destructing weapons, not a specific type of them, AL
sources told the Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The treaty is founded on three bases: the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT), completion of the draft treaty on
the Middle East, and the Israeli rejection to sign the NPT and to
subject its nuclear establishments to international supervision.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that most of Arab leaders, especially
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, have demanded freeing the Middle
East from nukes without any exceptions.
</P>
<P>
"All Arab countries want to denuclearize the Mideast. Such an
objective necessitates that Israel and the region's other
countries, including Turkey, Iran and Cyprus should also catch
up," said the same sources.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid has asked the U.S. and
Russia to drive Israel toward inclusion in the treaty and
subjection of its nuclear facilities to the comprehensive
monitoring system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
