<HEADLINE> Former Rwandan Minister Shot Dead in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Former Rwandan cabinet minister
Seth Sendashonga, who fled to Kenya in 1995, was shot dead here
Saturday afternoon, local reports quoted police sources as
saying.
</P>
<P>
More than two killers, one of them armed with an AK-47 rifle,
attacked Sendashonga during a thunderstorm just after 4 p.m. at a
busy junction near the downtown area which hosts a lot of
foreigners and diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Sendashonga died on the spot and his driver, a Kenyan, died on
the way to hospital, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
"There was blood all over the car and on the road," a witness
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The car used by the assassins was recovered on the other side
of Nairobi by the police later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sendashonga, a Hutu, who joined the Tutsi-dominated Rwandan
Patriotic Front (RPF) before it seized power in 1994, was
appointed as interior minister of Rwanda in July that year and
sacked in 1995. He then went into exile in Kenya as a leader of
the Rwandan opposition abroad.
</P>
<P>
He was regarded as a moderate Hutu opposed to the 1994
genocide in which more than 500,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus
were killed.
</P>
<P>
He survived a previous murder attempt on the outskirts of
Nairobi in June 1996 in which his nephew was critically wounded.
</P>
