<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export Earnings Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's total export earnings
rose by 23.5 percent to 169.5 billion taka (about 3.7 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first three quarters of the July 1997-June 1998
fiscal year from a year earlier, the national news agency BSS
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Of the total export earnings, raw jute and jute goods
contributed 13.1 billion taka (about 280 million dollars) while
non-jute items earned 156.4 billion taka (about 3.42 billion
dollars) during the period from July 1997 to March 1998, BSS said,
quoting the Dhaka Chamber of Commerce and Industry (DCCI).
</P>
<P>
Ready-made garments topped the list of the export earnings with
94.64 billion taka (about 2.06 billion dollars), accounting for
55.8 percent of the total, while their growth rate stood at 39.77
percent.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from other sectors all showed positive signs in the
period, the DCCI said.
</P>
<P>
However, earnings from some major export items including frozen
foods, jute goods and chemical products dropped during the period,
the DCCI added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
