<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fire Breaks Out in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 17 (Xinhua) -- A serious forest fire which broke
out in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region at 1:00
p.m. (Beijing Time) on May 13 had still not been brought under
control today.
</P>
<P>
The blaze broke out at a forest farm in Xing'an League
(county), in the middle part of the Greater Xing'an Range, and
rapidly spread to neighboring Hulun Buir League, to the northwest
of the range.
</P>
<P>
About 4,500 people, including forest farm staff, were
mobilized, as well as five planes and 100 vehicles, to fight the
blaze, which has destroyed 8,000 ha of forest land.
</P>
<P>
A local official said that the fire is difficult to put out
because of strong winds in the area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Laid-Off Workers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To ensure the livelihoods of laid-off workers and re-employment
of them is of great importance and urgency to the immediate
interests of workers, to the success of reform in state-owned
enterprises, and to the overall development and stability of the
country, the premier said.
</P>
<P>
"The mounting number of people laid off by state enterprises is
a combined result of the in-depth contradictions in our country's
economic growth over the past few years, and is an unavoidable
stage in the course of reform and development," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that reckless investment, project redundancy,
overproduction, lack of capital funds and overstaffing have for a
long time left many enterprises mired in problems, forcing them to
lay off workers or delay payment of their wages.
</P>
<P>
Because China at the moment has an incomplete social security
system, the basic livelihoods of laid-work workers cannot be
ensured, and social problems tend to crop up, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises and sectors suffering heavy losses and big
difficulties are those which employ too many people. But it will
be an inevitable trend that employees will become fewer, along with
technological advance and improved capital structure, he said.
</P>
<P>
The solution to the problem of overmanning in state enterprises
can only be attained on the basis of the current realities of the
country. To divert laid-off workers to other jobs and carry out
the re-employment program are crucial policy choices of the CPC
Central Committee and the State Council, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"These are entirely positive policies for relieving the current
economic and social contradictions and promoting reform and
development in the long run, and a necessary link in the process
of building a good social security system," Zhu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Laid-Off Workers (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu said that ensuring the basic livelihoods of laid-off
workers is essential before finding new jobs for them. In this
sense, the establishment of re-employment service centers is an
effective measure.
</P>
<P>
All enterprises which lay off workers must set up re-employment
service centers or similar organizations, which will be
responsible for providing basic living expenses, paying social
insurance fees for them, organizing vocational training and
helping them obtain new jobs.
</P>
<P>
In principle, one third of social insurance funds should come
from fiscal budgets of central and local governments, one third
from enterprises and the remainder from other sectors of the
society.
</P>
<P>
However, the proportions may vary in different localities. Poor
areas will get financial assistance from the central government,
the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu pointed out that retired workers from state enterprises
should be guaranteed comfort in their remaining years, because
they have made great contributions to the country. Pensions must
be paid on time, and any delayed part must be paid retroactively.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, legislation will be stepped up to ensure the
collection of pension funds, which can only be used to buy
treasury bonds. Anyone embezzling, misusing or wasting such funds
will be severely punished. In addition, workers in state-owned
enterprises may not retire before the legal age to do so,
according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
The premier explained that old-age and unemployment insurance,
guarantee of basic livelihoods for laid-off workers and basic living
expenses for urban residents are the three complementary systems
of the Chinese-style social security mechanism under the present
conditions. In the long term, a comprehensive social security system
covering all workers will be set up, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Laid-Off Workers (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu pointed out that the new situation demands boosting
re-employment with the reform measures in order to build an
employment mechanism in line with the development of the socialist
market economy.
</P>
<P>
To boost re-employment, it is essential to break away entirely
from the restraints of the old and decayed concepts of employment,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
People must abandon the concepts that employment only means
working at state- or collectively-owned enterprises, that there
are superior and inferior work posts, and that employees must
depend on the government for their "iron rice bowl," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu asked the concerned departments to guide laid-off workers
in selecting jobs according to their own will, starting new
careers through hard work and relying on the market to find new
jobs. Also, employers must change their concept of recruiting
staff, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said all walks of life should understand and respect
laid-off workers, and help them solve problems and increase
their confidence in getting new jobs.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that governments at all levels and the concerned
departments should offer necessary policy support and a favorable
social environment for those who are seeking jobs by themselves,
either individually or in groups.
</P>
<P>
Those departments should also depend on all social circles and
offer vocational training in various forms and at various levels,
in order to enable laid-off workers to match the demands of the
employment market as soon as possible, he added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they should actively develop and regulate the
labor market, establish and improve the employment information network
by modern means, and strengthen the management of the labor market
to protect the legitimate rights and interests of laid-off
workers, Zhu noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Laid-Off Workers (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu required the Party and government leaders at various levels
to be confident and work hard for the guarantee of the basic
livelihoods and re-employment of laid-off workers, because there
are favorable conditions for doing this work well.
</P>
<P>
First of all, all sides have reached a common understanding about
the central government's decisions on the reform of the state-owned
enterprises and the re-employment program.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the favorable macro conditions and the increasing
national strength have provided the material basis for solving the
re-employment problem.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, local governments and enterprises have accumulated
rich experience in this matter, and the country is politically and
socially stable, Zhu said, noting that everyone must grasp the
current favorable opportunity and handle well the re-employment
work to lay a basis for long-term stability.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also required that this work be done in line with this
year's economic growth target, and that local governments must
firmly carry out each measure stipulated by the central government.
</P>
<P>
He said local governments must attach great importance to grain
production, and carry out the reform of the grain marketing system
to the letter.
</P>
<P>
The policy of purchasing surplus grain at protective prices
must be firmly implemented, Zhu said, while local governments must
make sure that grain is sold at the market price, and that there
are no further management losses.
</P>
<P>
As for financial institutions, more positive measures should be
taken to boost the economic growth in the course of deepening the
financial reform, he said.
</P>
<P>
Circulating funds should be guaranteed for profitable products,
support be increased for projects under construction, assessment
of new projects be accelerated, and more measures be taken to help
infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the taxation departments must work harder in
collecting and managing taxes, and the foreign trade departments
should strive to expand exports and crack down on smuggling, Zhu
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
