<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat to Visit S. Africa in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Liberation
Organization (PLO) leader Yasser Arafat is to pay a state visit
to South Africa in August, South African president's office
confirmed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
President Nelson Mandela and Arafat would discuss "what heads
of state normally talk about", and Arafat would brief Mandela on
the Middle East peace process, spokesman Parks Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
The visit, Arafat's first to South Africa since he attended
Mandela's inauguration in 1994, would last more than 24 hours,
but the exact dates had not been fixed, Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing the idea that South Africa's invitation to Arafat
indicated the country's support for the Palestinians in the
Middle East peace process, the spokesman said the South African
government had always supported the whole process rather than any
of the sides.
</P>
<P>
The visit was essentially about bilateral relations and there
was no plan of involving other southern African countries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the spiritual leader of the radical
Palestinian movement Hamas, Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, was refused a
visa by the South African government after the Palestinian
National Authority reportedly pressured it to stop the visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
