<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, China Qualify for Semi-Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Both defending champions
Indonesia and runners-up China qualified for the semi-finals after
they took an unassailable lead in their respective groups at the
17th Uber Cup women's badminton world team championships finals
here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Joining them in the semi-finals are South Korea and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesians of Group B were stretched to five games before
taking the tie against the Netherlands 3-2 and China won over
Japan 4-1 in Group A, both on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In other actions of the day, South Korea beat England 4-1 in
Group B and Denmark of Group A downed Hong Kong, China, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
Leading Group B are Indonesia and South Korea, which had each
won two ties so far, with only one remaining. Group A leaders are
now China and Denmark, winning two ties each. They each have one
more match to play, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
China's third-ranked Gong Zhichao was upset by Japan's
31st-ranked Yasuki Mizui 11-4, 1-11, 3-11, in the day's biggest
surprise.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Gong has been thought as one of the most
hopeful successors of the current world number one and world
singles champion Ye Zhaoying, who is now 24.
</P>
<P>
"Technically speaking, Gong should not have lost the match. But
she seemed to be under much pressure from herself during the match
which foiled her efforts to play her normal game," said Chinese
coach Li Lingwei.
</P>
<P>
And Gong failed to control the game after the change of ends in
the match as there was a wind over the court, Li said.
</P>
<P>
But this loss would not affect the selection of the singles
players for the team's next tie against Denmark on Wednesday, Li
said. "We'll always field the strongest team," she added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's trial use of a new combination for the doubles
proved to be a failure on Sunday. The eighth-ranked pair of
Indarti Soiliana and Denyana Lomban was split as Isoliana had to
team with Finarshi to take on the Dutch pair of Nicole van Hooren
and Lotte Jonathans. The Indonesians were beaten 15-18, 15-3,
9-15.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia also lost the second singles, with 32nd-ranked
Meiluawati losing to Brenda Beenhakker 12-9, 5-11, 7-11.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Cup Finals will continue on Monday, when Indonesia will
take on South Korea and Malaysia meet the Netherlands in Group B
while in Group A, China will play Hong Kong, China, and Denmark
face Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
