<HEADLINE> China Aiding the Disabled (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- China held a series of nationwide
activities to mark today's eighth National Day for Aiding the
Disabled, which takes "poverty-relief" as its theme.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, and leading officials of the All-China Women's
Federation and China Disabled Persons Federation (CDPF) visited
two poverty-stricken families of disabled persons in the Xuanwu
district of the capital city this morning.
</P>
<P>
At Wangfujing, a downtown commercial center, a rehabilitation
consultation service for the disabled was held, with the
attendance of experts on medical treatment and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
An inaugural ceremony for a service agency for the disabled was
held in Daxing, a suburban county of Beijing, which will provide
various kinds of assistance for the disabled to escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
Deng Pufang, chairman of the CDPF, went to Yongqing and Haixing
counties in north China's Hebei Province this morning, visiting
rural disabled families and attending meetings calling for helping
the disabled shake off poverty.
</P>
<P>
Mu Wengyue, a disabled resident of Tianjin, the biggest port
city in north China, received financial assistance of 500 yuan
(about 62 US dollars) from the Tianjin Welfare Fund for the
Disabled this morning, as did 11 other handicapped people.
</P>
<P>
"As many as 5,000 of the city's total 336,000 disabled people
have shaken off poverty with help from the general public," said
Li Yuzhang, chairman of the executive council of the Tianjin
Disabled Persons Federation, at a meeting held in the city today
to mark the occasion.
</P>
</TEXT>
