<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vajpayee Pledges Not to Use Nukes for Aggression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee assured the international community Sunday that his
country would never use its nuclear program as a "weapon of
aggression."
</P>
<P>
There would be no change in India's "long and vigorous pursuit
of peace in the region and the world," Vajpayee was quoted by the
Press Trust of India as saying in the port city of Kochi in the
southwestern state of Kerala.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to reassure the international community that the
nuclear tests will make no change in India's long and vigorous
pursuit of peace in the region and the world. Ours will never be
the weapons of aggression," said the Indian prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating an institute of medical sciences and research in
Kochi, Vajpayee said the tests would help India emerge as a
nuclear weapon state, asserting that India is surrounded by
countries having nuclear capabilities.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to be taken by surprise," said Vajpayee, who
first declared India a nuclear weapon state last Friday.
</P>
<P>
When India conducted five nuclear tests last week, thereby
announcing its emergence as a nuclear weapon state, Vajpayee said,
"we did so on the basis of our own sound and careful appraisal of
the regional and global security scenario."
</P>
<P>
He repeated his position that India could not succumb to
pressures to sign what he called discriminatory treaties like the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and the non-proliferation treaties
which he said have utterly failed to bring about any progress in
global nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to all Indians to further strengthen the sense of
national unity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
