<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Aiding the Disabled (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
People in Shanghai, China's biggest city, marked today by
providing consultation services, staging open-air cultural
performances and holding donation activities for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
Feng Guoqin, deputy mayor of Shanghai, visited a flower and
bird market run by five disabled persons. The market manager gave
him a report on the market's development. Feng, moved and
delighted by the report, presented the market workers with a
large-screen color television set.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five hearing-aids, worth a total of 100,000 yuan (about
12,000 US dollars), were donated today by the US Bahmann
Foundation and Starkey Labs Inc. to deaf people in Wuhan, capital
of central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The donation announcement came at the provincial rehabilitation
center for deaf children, where the Foundation's executive
director and the manager of the China branch of Starkey Labs were
conducting diagnoses for elderly people and children with hearing
problems.
</P>
<P>
The corporation's manager said that it would donate 345 more
hearing-aids to Chinese deaf people this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 disabled people in Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, went to the city's Cultural Park to
participate in various activities, in spite of heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
The city's telecommunications bureau has offered a 50 percent
discount to disabled who apply for telephones. Nearly 300 disabled
people received this preferential treatment this morning.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere across the country, local authorities visited
disabled people and their families, as well as needy ones, to
extend their sympathy and support, and various preferential
treatment or financial assistance programs were kicked off both in
urban and rural areas to help the disabled overcome difficulties.
</P>
<P>
China has a disabled population of more than 60 million. The
Chinese government has made the promotion of the welfare of the
disabled an important part of its endeavors to protect human
rights in the country.
</P>
<P>
China's Law on Protecting the Disabled, issued in December
1990, designated the third Sunday in May as the National Day for
Aiding the Disabled.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century China intends to be able to feed and
clothe all its disabled people, help one million disabled people
overcome their disabilities to various degrees, and ensure that
about 80 percent of handicapped children receive schooling and 80
percent of handicapped adults find jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
