<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment to Improve North China Harbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei Province
is to attract foreign investment to improve the construction and
efficiency of its five harbors on Bohai Bay.
</P>
<P>
A local official said here today that Hebei has 460 km of
coastline on Bohai Bay, and there are many suitable places there
for building major harbors.
</P>
<P>
The province will use 98.8 million US dollars -- 48.4 million
US dollars from foreign investors -- to set up two 25,000-dwt
berth with 3.8 million tons of annual handling capacity at the
Qinhuangdao Port, which can handle a total of 100 million tons of
cargo a year.
</P>
<P>
With 78 million yuan in foreign funds, half of the total
investment, Hebei is to build a second berth with four million
tons of annual handling capacity at the Jingtang Harbor, where at
the moment 7.8 million tons of cargoes can be handled by the first
berth, the official said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the province will set up two 35,000 dwt
berths at the Jingtang Harbor for handling coal, and build a berth
for 200,000 dwt cargo ships to transport raw materials for iron
and steel enterprises in north China.
</P>
<P>
Also with foreign investment, the province will build eight
berths with a total of 10 million tons of annual handling capacity
at Shanhaiguan Harbor, the official said, adding that a six-berth
foreign-funded harbor will also be set up there to handle sundry
goods, building materials, containers and salt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
