<HEADLINE> Beijing to Carry Out 10 "Aid-the-Disabled" Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Meng Xuenong, deputy mayor of
Beijing, said here today -- the National Day for Aiding the
Disabled -- that the municipal government will carry out ten
projects this year to help the disabled in the city.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are 460,000 disabled people in
Beijing, accounting for 4.5 percent of the city's total
population.
</P>
<P>
The 10 projects are as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- Providing jobs for 1,000 disabled people and vocational
training for 5,000.
</P>
<P>
To date, the employment rate of disabled people in the city has
reached over 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Conducting free cataract extraction operations for 250
poverty-stricken blind people and providing related medical
instruments for 50 counties and townships.
</P>
<P>
-- Enrolling 26 disabled students in three-year higher
education courses in advertising design and acupuncture and
moxibustion at Beijing United University.
</P>
<P>
-- Providing 100,000 yuan for scholarships for students from
600 disabled families.
</P>
<P>
-- Building specially-designed public facilities for the
disabled in a number of streets, theaters, schools and residential
quarters.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has so far built 150 km of special walkways for the
blind.
</P>
<P>
-- Issuing poverty-relief loans for the disabled in three
counties in the city.
</P>
<P>
-- Guaranteeing 230 yuan per month for 3,000 chronically
jobless disabled people.
</P>
<P>
-- Installing 100 "help the disabled" donation boxes in
department stores and hotels.
</P>
<P>
-- Selecting a group of law firms to provide priority service for
the disabled.
</P>
<P>
-- Setting up two or three cultural activity centers for the
disabled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
