<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Disabled Farmer Turns to Raising Rabbits (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- When Li Guozheng lost his right arm
in an accident 23 years ago, he thought that he had also lost the
ability to feed the family, as his wife is disabled also.
</P>
<P>
Now Li, 62, earns at least 2,000 yuan (about 240 US dollars) a
month by breeding rabbits, whose soft fur is sought by garment
factories and whose meat is becoming increasingly popular on
Chinese dinner tables.
</P>
<P>
"I'll breed more rabbits this year," he said, ``and earn 4,000
yuan to 5,000 yuan a month."
</P>
<P>
Li's family has benefitted from a special loan project which
grants a handicapped person some 1,000 yuan to 2,000 yuan to set
up in business.
</P>
<P>
To qualify, the loan applicant must be able to work and
promise to pay the loan back, said Tian Bin, an official with the
China Disabled Persons' Federation (CDPF), which sponsors the
project.
</P>
<P>
"Out of the 17 million poverty-stricken handicapped people in
China, 14 million have the ability to do some work," Tian
said. "Unfortunately, they tend to be shunned because of their
deformities, and lack financial and technological support."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Disabled Farmer Turns to Raising Rabbits (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Providing loans has proved to be much more effective than
simply allocating relief funds, because the recipients must make
every effort to earn to pay back the loans, and not just live on
government aid," Tian said.
</P>
<P>
The official, who was visiting Li Guozheng's village to check
the use of the loans, told Xinhua today that the CDPF and the
Agricultural Bank of China plan to provide 500 million yuan in
loans to the disabled every year during the 1998-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
"We're pressed for time, because the government has set the
year 2000 as the deadline for helping all the handicapped in the
country to shake off poverty," he said.
</P>
<P>
Not only Tian but the whole country has no longer than three
years left to fulfill the goal set four years ago to enable
some 80 million people living in poverty to have enough to eat and
wear.
</P>
<P>
At presernt, China has 50 million poor people, of which one
third are handicapped.
</P>
<P>
Those who are disabled and live in areas far from cities may
not be as lucky as the Lis.
</P>
<P>
"That's why we chose 'Helping Poor Disabled People' as the
theme of today's nationwide activities," Tian said, referring to
the eighth National Day for Aiding the Disabled.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the project will cover about 500 counties across
the country.  
</P>
