<HEADLINE> Iran Invites Global Bidding for Pipeline Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran has invited international
bidding for the project of building a pipeline to transfer oil
from the Caspian Sea to the Persian Gulf, local daily Iran News
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The National Iranian Oil Company (NIOC) said the 392-kilometer
pipeline, linking Neka in the northern province of Mazadaran, and
Rey near the capital Tehran, will be built through exchange
programs with Iranian oil.
</P>
<P>
The NIOC estimated the project would cost 300 to 400 million
U.S. dollars in a period of two years, hoping the construction
would begin by the end of the current Iranian calendar year (March
21, 1999).
</P>
<P>
The pipeline is to have a daily transferring capacity of
380,000 barrels, and probably make Iran the quickest and cheapest
route for shipping oil from the Caspian Sea region to the outside
world, earlier reports said.
</P>
<P>
Iran announced the construction of this pipeline after some
Caspian littoral states decided to lay a pipeline on the Caspian
seabed between Turkmenistan and Azerbaijan Republic, a move
rejected by Iran on the ground that it might pose a serious threat
to the sea's environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
