<HEADLINE> Coffee Output Plunges in N. Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Coffee production in Arusha
Region in north Tanzania plunged to 2,000 tons, compared with
10,000 tons in the past years, Sunday News said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The coffee crop co-ordinator of the region, Zebedayo Swai,
said that the decrease of coffee production in the region was
caused by drought and lack of inputs in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He said production of the crop is expected to increase this
year blessed by heavy rains linked to the El Nino weather
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Swai said the Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives has
started to take special measures to increase the production of
coffee in the region. The measures include supervising nurseries
of coffee seedlings and conducting seminars for concerned
officers and farmers.
</P>
<P>
The co-ordinator said about 615,000 coffee seedlings have been
planted in nurseries and 200,000 seedlings sold to farmers,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Arusha region has 21,000 hectares of coffee, 18,000 hectares
of which are owned by small farmers. The rest are estates.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's coffee is mainly produced in Arusha, Kilimanjaro
and Mbeya regions. Coffee export earnings over the past three
years totaled 120 million U.S. Dollars and accounted for 15
percent of all commodity exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
