<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy to Return to Cyprus in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
said U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke will return to Cyprus in June
to discuss procedural issues relating to the resumption of peace
negotiation between the island's two communities.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation on Sunday quoted Clerides
as saying that Holbrooke is expected to visit Cyprus after the
European Union (EU) summit to be held in Cardiff, Wales, in June.
</P>
<P>
"His visit will focus on procedural issues and not the essence
of the Cyprus problem," Clerides said. He added that all parties
involved in finding a settlement in Cyprus are expecting the
results of the Cardiff summit.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, who was appointed by U.S. President Bill Clinton as
his emissary for Cyprus last year, was on the island early this
month in a bid to resume negotiations between the two communities.
</P>
<P>
His efforts stumbled on preconditions set by Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash, for the recognition of his self-styled
regime in northern Cyprus and the withdrawal of Cyprus'
application to join the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops on the island and took over the northern third in the
aftermath of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", which was recognized only
by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Denktash walked out of the U.N.-sponsored peace talks with the
Greek Cypriot leader Clerides last summer to protest the EU's
decision to open accession talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
He has since insisted that the peace talks could be resumed
only if they will be held on "state-to-state" basis.
</P>
<P>
So far the negotiations have been carried out by Clerides and
Denktash in their capacity as leaders of their respective
communities, in accordance with the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Cardiff summit is expected to tackle EU relations with
Turkey, which failed to be included as one of the first candidates
for EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
