<HEADLINE> Oil Spill Ruins Fishery Resource in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The recent oil spill in part of the
Bakassi Peninsula in southeastern Nigeria where the big-name
Mobil is operating has deteriorated fishery resources in the
area.
</P>
<P>
For the past three months, local people, seeing more fish
floating in the sea than ever before, have been complaining of
"Akpa Ifonke", a native saying meaning "the sea is bad", the New
Nigerian reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Faced with the persistent poor catch due to the pollution
effect, ignorant fishermen have invited a clergyman to offer
special prayers to God for better fish landing.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation is yet to improve despite the effort at
divine intervention, the official daily said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, cases of abdominal pain have been on the rise in
recent times since the people's source of drinking water is the
sea, it said, quoting Lt.-Col. Danladi Kaka, the commanding
officer of the Nigerian army in charge of that area.
</P>
<P>
Briefing a visiting team of Mobil assessment and verification
officials at the weekend, Lt.-Col. Kaka said oil films were
noticed everywhere in the area and four out-board engines
belonging to his command had been damaged.
</P>
<P>
Admitted that the fishermen's claim were not baseless, the
team leader said the team would analyze the specimen collected
and make recommendations to Mobil for payment of compensation,
which he assured would be done soon.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the team is to ensure that Mobil was not
over-taxed and the people not under-paid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
