<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dar Vendor Cries over Eggs Eaten by Crows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 17 (Xinhua) -- A Dar es Salaam vendor has
suffered a loss of more than 70 U.S. Dollars after his eggs were
spilled and eaten by Indian crows, according to a report by the
Sunday Observer.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened as Matiku Wambura, the vendor, failed to
negotiate a sharp curve and fell off his bicycle when he was
heading toward the Kariakoo Central Market to deliver eggs to his
clients Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As he stood up, Wambura could not believe his eyes -- the eggs
had become delicious meals of hungry crows flying down from
surrounding trees!
</P>
<P>
Although two women nearby had came to the rescue using clubs,
stones and tree branches to disperse the birds, Wambura salvaged
only 129 eggs in the end.
</P>
<P>
He said the crows had devoured 471 eggs making him lose 47,100
Shillings (about 71 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Indian crows are unwelcome in Dar es Salaam because they not
only steal people's food, valuable items such as gold chains, but
also transmit diseases and make noises.
</P>
<P>
The crows are also aggressive predators to domestic poultry
and other bird species but they themselves have no natural enemy,
said an official with the Wildlife Conservation Society of
Tanzania (WCST).
</P>
<P>
Since last year, residents have trapped and killed more than
9,000 Indian crows in the city with special traps made of wire
mesh and timber with the help of the Canadian Fund for Local
Initiative.
</P>
<P>
The crows originated from Asia and were introduced in the
Zanzibar isles one century ago. They were brought to Dar es
Salaam around 1955 by unknown people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Red Crescent Society Calls for More Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Red Crescent Society Sunday
called on non-governmental organizations (NGOs) to provide more
aid for Iraqi people who are suffering under the U.N. embargo.
</P>
<P>
Sadik Hamed Alwash, chairman of the society, told a press
conference that Iraq was still in urgent need of humanitarian aid
despite the U.N. oil-for-food deal and the work of international
humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
Alwash said over 5,000 children have been registered dead due
to severe shortage of food and medicine. Iraqi official figures
indicated that about 1.5 million people, mainly elderly and
children, have perished since the end of the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal adopted in December 1996 allowed Iraq to
sell limited oil worth 2 billion U.S. dollars each six months to
buy food, medicine for its people.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. expanded the deal, which is now in its third phase,
earlier this year by permitting Iraq to boost its oil exports to
5.2 billion dollars in its fourth phase.
</P>
<P>
The third phase expires on June 3.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iraqi side has said its exports in the fourth
phase will be based on the availability of spare parts to upgrade
its oil production facilities, but will not exceed 4 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The chairman urged international humanitarian organizations to
continue to work for the lifting of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
Humanitarian aid could only alleviate part of Iraqi people's
sufferings, he said.
</P>
<P>
The economic sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait cannot be lifted until the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) certifies that it has rid itself of long-range missiles
and weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM last month told the U.N. Security Council reviewing the
sanctions that there was virtually no progress in verifying Iraq's
banned-weapon-free claims, which led to the maintaining of the
sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
