<HEADLINE> Roundup: Dhaka Makes Progress in Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has scored encouraging
progress in its economic reforms which are aimed at achieving a
sustained high growth rate and significantly reducing poverty.
</P>
<P>
The progress is mainly the result of the systematic and
coordinate approach to reforms in the country's financial sector,
trade, capital market and privatization, which the present
government has adopted since coming to power in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
In May 1997, the government formulated a comprehensive
restructuring plan to introduce legal and institutional reforms in
the financial sector, with the Bangladesh Bank, the country's
central bank, charged with developing action programs to
strengthen supervision and monitoring of the banking system.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the government's bank borrowing was reduced
remarkably to 3.44 billion taka (about 75 million U.S. dollars)
during the July 1997-January 1997 period from 9.15 billion taka
(about 200 million dollars) in the corresponding period of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to deal with the heavy burden of default loans
totaling about 140 billion taka ( 3.04 billion dollars) at
present, a bankruptcy law has been passed by the parliament and a
number of courts set up for trying default loan cases and
expediting loan recovery.
</P>
<P>
And President Shahabuddin Ahmed suggested recently the
establishment of special tribunals to deal with the loan
defaulters.
</P>
<P>
Despite the progress made so far, the financial sector is still
beset with problems such as inefficient service delivery, lack of
new services and absent of effective competition, and the central
bank is yet to fully enforce the desired level of discipline,
according to the Finance Ministry's Report on Progress in Reforms
(1996-98) issued recently.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, further work is needed especially in the areas of
loan-recovery and bank management, human resources development,
commercial bank restructuring, privatization of national
commercial banks, and strengthening of the central bank for
improving the intermediation work in the commercial banking
sector, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the field of trade, the Bangladeshi government has pledged
its commitment to the pursuit of progressive trade liberalization
through further removal of quantitative restrictions and
moderation of protection.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has recently approved an Import Policy Order, which
was formulated for the first time for a term of five years instead
of two years. The government hopes that the policy, which could be
reviewed every year in case of necessity, would further reduce the
quantitative restrictions, and help create a stable long-term
favorable investment climate in the country. ( More )


=05170834
NNNN
16:41 16:41 g # HAB
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
