<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Hold First Stockpiled Goods Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Stockpiled industrial goods will
be auctioned in China's largest industrial center of Shanghai for
the first time in its history.
</P>
<P>
The auction is to be held on May 26-27 at the Huadong (East
China) Trade Square of Shanghai, said Yang Zezheng, deputy general
manager of the municipal stockpiled industrial goods swap center,
at a press conference held Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thirty kinds of stocked products to go on sale will include
mechanical and electrical equipment, auto spare parts, second-hand
motor vehicles, rubber tyre and chemical raw materials, involving
a total value of 150 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some of the products will be sold without any opening bid. As
their list prices are fairly low, there can be possibilities for
appreciations, said Fan Ganping, who will be in charge of the
auction.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 enterprises in the fields of metallurgy,
electricity, textile and light industry will send representatives
to the auction.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's industrial sector has a reserve of 4.6 billion
yuan-worth (554 million US dollars) of manufactured goods by the
end of 1997. To help alleviate the burden of these enterprises,
the municipal government set up a swap center for stockpiled goods
early this year. And 1.8 billion yuan-worth ((217 million US
dollars) of good kept in stock have so far been sold out by the
means of holding sales exhibitions or through other channels.
</P>
</TEXT>
