<HEADLINE> Zambia's Public Prosecution Head Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
has suspended Director of Public Prosecution Meebelo Kalima from
duty pending investigations by a tribunal of judges to determine
his continued tenure of office.
</P>
<P>
This move was announced in a statement issued here Saturday by
Presidential Press Aide Richard Sakala to Zambia Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
Sakala also revealed that President Chiluba has since
appointed a three-member tribunal to determine the question of
Kalima's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
The presidential press aide, however, neither disclosed the
reasons why Kalima has been suspended nor announced who will be
acting in Kalima's absence.
</P>
<P>
Kalima was, in 1996, together with four others appointed as
member of the Electoral Commission. And in 1997, Chiluba
appointed him as Director of Public Prosecution.
</P>
<P>
There is speculation that the suspension of Kalima from office
may be relevant to the delayed trial of the 82 treason accused
members who were allegedly involved in last October's foiled
military coup. 
</P>
