<HEADLINE> Nigeria Promulgates Parliament Decrees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 17 (Xinhua) -- A decree constituting the National
Assembly, or parliament, of Nigeria, was at the weekend signed
into law by the head of state, General Sani Abacha, the Post
Express reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The new decree, entitled the National Assembly Basci
Promulgation Decree of 1998, provides for a four-year term for
parliament while members are expected to sit 181 days in a year.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the National Assembly Election
Tribunal has also been constituted.
</P>
<P>
The decree prohibits a member of parliament from performing
the function of the executive as long as he remains a member of
the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
The provisions of the new decree are reportedly in parts a
re-election of the contents of the yet to be promulgated 1995
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The election of the national assembly was held three weeks ago
to produce 109 senators and 360 members of the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Despite a low turn-out, there is no sign the authorities will
announce a re-election while the final result is yet to be
released by the National Electoral Commission of Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
