<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Lower Economic Ties with Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran has announced to lower its
"economic ties" with Buenos Aires, after Argentina recalled all
diplomats here except the charge d'affaires, and reduced
diplomatic relations "to the minimum."
</P>
<P>
Tehran radio on Sunday quoted Foreign Ministry spokesman
Mahmoud Mohammadi as saying that Iran made the decision following
the repeated "baseless accusations" that Iran were behind two
blasts in Buenos Aires which killed 114 people.
</P>
<P>
Iran has vehemently denied it was involved in the bombings in
1992 and 1994 which destroyed the Israeli Embassy in Buenos Aires
and the Jewish center respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman said "we have warned the Argentine charge
d'affaires in Tehran that Iran will reconsider its ties with
Argentina" if Buenos Aires continues its allegations against
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman failed to mention what measures will be
actually taken to effect the reduction of "economic ties."
</P>
<P>
The Argentine diplomat was summoned to the Foreign Ministry
Thursday and warned that the Argentine accusations would have
serious negative impact on bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
After the 1994 bomb explosion, an Iranian national Manouchehr
Motamer offered information to the Argentine authorities,
incriminating Iranian diplomats in the bomb blasts.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran claimed that the Iranian citizen was a
"fraud" and his evidence had no judicial value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Dhaka Makes Progress in Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The cabinet has also approved recently an Export Policy Order
for a five-year period, which is designed to effect sustained
increase in export earnings within the quickest possible time by
diversifying export base and increasing export quantity.
</P>
<P>
As a result of conducive policies and a judicious incentive
structure, the country's exports have been growing rapidly. Annual
exports grew nearly 14 percent in the 1996-97 fiscal year against
12 percent in previous fiscal year. Export growth in the current
fiscal year up to February 1998 was 16.5 percent compared with the
same period in the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The highest rate of customs duty has been brought down from 50
percent to 45 percent in fiscal 1996-97 and then to 42.5 percent
in 1997-98, and to rationalize the tariff structure and enhance
protection to emerging industries in the country, import duties on
certain raw materials and spares have also been reduced.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government is planning steps to remove the
remaining anomalies in the tariff structure and further reduce
dispersion of tariff rates.
</P>
<P>
So far Bangladesh has two stock exchange markets respectively
located in Dhaka and the southeast seaport city of Chittagong,
which have amassed huge amount of capital for the country's
economic development.
</P>
<P>
To broaden investors' participation and to improve efficiency,
the government is setting up a national stock exchange and will
further relax the restrictions on foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, regulations allowing merchant banks' operations were
issued, and to date, the stock exchange commission has issued
merchant bank licenses to 17 companies in a bid to improve
institutional support, heighten the level of their participation
in the securities market and to further activate the capital
market.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's state-owned enterprises (SOEs), most of which have
long suffered losses due to reasons like inefficiency and
mismanagement, are in the process of privatization, an important
component of the government's overall market-oriented development
strategy.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the privatization process, the government
formulated the Privatization Bill 1998 this year providing the
legal framework for privatizing SOEs, and reconstituted the
country's Board of Privatization (BOP) to include parliament
members, private sectors' representatives and professionals.
</P>
<P>
Privatization cells have been set up in loss-making SOEs under
different ministries for assisting the BOP in identifying,
preparing, processing, implementing and monitoring SOEs for
privatization.
</P>
<P>
To help the affected workers in privatizing the SOEs, the board
is planning to introduce a training program to develop marketable
skills for their re-employment such as by building up viable
micro-enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Since the BOP was formed in 1993, 12 industries were privatized
up to 1996. And since June 1996, the privatization process has
been speeded up.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996-97 fiscal year, the government finalized the
sale of 18 enterprises to private firms, and the BOP has
identified 54 enterprises for privatization so far in the current
fiscal year (July 1997-June 1998).
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, as one of the least developed countries in the
world with a weak economic base, Bangladesh still faces arduous
tasks ahead on its way of economic reform. In order to expedite
its economic development and poverty alleviation, the country
needs to make more painstaking efforts in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Dhaka Makes Progress in Economic Reforms ( By Hao Fusheng, Pan Yunzhao ) (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has scored encouraging
progress in its economic reforms which are aimed at achieving a
sustained high growth rate and significantly reducing poverty.
</P>
<P>
The progress is mainly the result of the systematic and
coordinate approach to reforms in the country's financial sector,
trade, capital market and privatization, which the present
government has adopted since coming to power in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
In May 1997, the government formulated a comprehensive
restructuring plan to introduce legal and institutional reforms in
the financial sector, with the Bangladesh Bank, the country's
central bank, charged with developing action programs to
strengthen supervision and monitoring of the banking system.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the government's bank borrowing was reduced
remarkably to 3.44 billion taka (about 75 million U.S. dollars)
during the July 1997-January 1997 period from 9.15 billion taka
(about 200 million dollars) in the corresponding period of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to deal with the heavy burden of default loans
totaling about 140 billion taka ( 3.04 billion dollars) at
present, a bankruptcy law has been passed by the parliament and a
number of courts set up for trying default loan cases and
expediting loan recovery.
</P>
<P>
And President Shahabuddin Ahmed suggested recently the
establishment of special tribunals to deal with the loan
defaulters.
</P>
<P>
Despite the progress made so far, the financial sector is still
beset with problems such as inefficient service delivery, lack of
new services and absent of effective competition, and the central
bank is yet to fully enforce the desired level of discipline,
according to the Finance Ministry's Report on Progress in Reforms
(1996-98) issued recently.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, further work is needed especially in the areas of
loan-recovery and bank management, human resources development,
commercial bank restructuring, privatization of national
commercial banks, and strengthening of the central bank for
improving the intermediation work in the commercial banking
sector, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the field of trade, the Bangladeshi government has pledged
its commitment to the pursuit of progressive trade liberalization
through further removal of quantitative restrictions and
moderation of protection.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has recently approved an Import Policy Order, which
was formulated for the first time for a term of five years instead
of two years. The government hopes that the policy, which could be
reviewed every year in case of necessity, would further reduce the
quantitative restrictions, and help create a stable long-term
favorable investment climate in the country. ( More )

=05170747
NNNN
15:54 15:55 g # HAB
</P>
</TEXT>
