<HEADLINE> Jaffna Mayor Killed in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- the mayor of Sri Lanka's northern
Jaffna town, Sarojini Yogeswaran, was shot dead by a lone gunman
on Sunday, informed sources here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Yogeswaran, 60, was attacked at her home in
Jaffna city, about 260 kilometers from Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Yogeswaran, a member of the Tamil United Liberation Front
(TULF) was sworn in March this year as the first Mayor of former
Tamil rebel northern strong-hold Jaffna since 1984.
</P>
<P>
During the local elections in January this year, Yogeswaran
said Tamil rebels were responsible for the killing of her husband
who represented Jaffna city in the country's parliament from 1977
to 1983 and was assassinated in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Jaffna city in northern Sri Lanka was recaptured by government
troops from the Tamil rebels in December, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting for a separate state in the
north and east of the country since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The government said in 1996 that more than 50,000 people had
been killed in the 14-year-old ethnic war. Since then several
thousand more rebels and government soldiers have been killed or
wounded in fierce fighting in the north and east. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
