<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi Preparing for 1999 Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Malawi is gearing up for its second
free legislative and presidential elections scheduled for May
1999, amid calls to reform the electoral law.
</P>
<P>
The country's Electoral Commission, which is mandated to set
the date for legislative and presidential elections, has worked
hard to have reforms to the electoral law passed by parliament,
according to Zambia Daily Mail published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Government officials say that the legislators will legalize
fraudulent elections if parliament does not pass the
parliamentary and presidential elections amendment bill and the
electoral commission bill.
</P>
<P>
Supreme Court judge Anastasia Msosa, who chairs the Electoral
Commission, says the legal reforms will empower the institution
to guarantee a free vote during parliamentary, presidential and
local government elections.
</P>
<P>
Proposed reforms provide for an independent secretariat for
the commission, with a permanent chief elections officer
appointed by the president on recommendation of the public
appointments committee.
</P>
<P>
The officer would take over responsibility from the clerk of
parliament, who doubles for the elections office on a part-time
basis.
</P>
<P>
The amended act will also mandate the courts to impose a
punitive 50,000 Malawian Kwacha (2,000 U.S. Dollars) penalty for
those who "receive, keep or use" another person's voter
certificate. The fine will run concurrently with a mandatory
seven-year goal term.
</P>
<P>
The reforms also propose the use of a single ballot paper and
the setting up of polling stations in military and police bases
-- to enable the security personnel and their families to vote
two days prior to the polling day so that they can effectively
man stations on voting days.
</P>
<P>
While voting in the past was marred by numerous incidents of
vote buying, intimidation, mass defections of party members and
the alleged kidnaping of candidates, the 1999 elections promise
to be even more controversial, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Political parties have already started flouting the existing
electoral law and the electoral committee admits it currently
lacks the mechanism to deal with the issues.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian government, which has completely shut out the
opposition voice on national airwaves, is using the radio as a
way to kick-start its campaign.
</P>
<P>
Party functionaries from President Bakili Muluzi's ruling
United Democratic Front, use public functions where Muluzi
usually addresses the public and which are given full coverage on
national radio, to air heavy criticism of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
An outspoken member of opposition Malawi Congress Party thinks
the Electoral Commission in its present form is irrelevant and
partisan and the members should immediately be replaced by more
credible personalities.
</P>
<P>
However, the commission declares these accusations unfair and
unfounded in the absence of enabling legal machinery.
</P>
<P>
It says it is taking time to slowly, but thoroughly, sort out
the electoral mess "to strengthen Malawi's fragile democracy"
before the 1999 general elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Album Tells of Japanese Troops' Atrocities against China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- A photo collection of nearly 1,000
photos depicting atrocities committed by Japanese troops against
China during the second world war has been discovered in Shenyang,
capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Compiled by the Japanese naval troops in 1940, the photo book
entitled "Album in Commemoration of Incidents in China" depicted
major battles launched by the Japanese ground and air forces and
marine troops in China during 1937-1939.
</P>
<P>
The photos show scenes of reconnaissance by Japanese intruding
forces, houses gutted by fire, bombed bridges, sunken warships,
slain Chinese soldiers and innocent civilians, and battle sketches
of bombed sites and major battle fields.
</P>
<P>
The album was found coincidentally at the time when a Japanese
movie -- "Pride, an Instant in a Lifetime" which whitewashes
Japanese aggressor troops and sings the praises of Hideki Tojo,
the top Japanese war criminal during the World War II -- is being
shown in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The album had been edited mainly for the Japanese army to show
off its military actions in China, but only to leave behind the
irrefutable evidence of its towering crimes, said Xing Anchen, a
professor with Liaoning University.
</P>
<P>
The professor noted that Japan has tightly covered up its
history of aggression against China over the past five decades, so
it was really rare that such an album is available in China today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the album could be confidential materials with an
extremely small number of printing.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Hongyu, vice-chairman of the Liaoning Provincial
Association for Promotion of Sino-Japan Industrial Economy,
obtained the album from the son of a former Japanese naval
lieutenant general while working in Japan, and he then brought it
back to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
