<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Rejects Weapons Search Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti National Assembly
Saturday night rejected a government-proposed bill to search for
fire-arms in citizens' houses on grounds that it violates the
sanctity of the home and the Islamic Sharia law.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 36 members who were present to vote, 27 were
against, five for and four abstained, according to local
newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The law was in effect for a two-year period from 1992 after
the Gulf War and the government has been trying to reactivate it
since its temporary life expired.
</P>
<P>
It allows Interior Ministry security forces to inspect any
residential area and search houses in its vicinity to look for
illegal arms, with the permission from local public prosecutor to
begin random inspections.
</P>
<P>
An unknown number of fire-arms were left over in the residents'
hands after the Gulf War and many have not been handed over to the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The parliament members insisted that the bill violates the
Constitution and they doubted the credibility of police officers
conducting such searches.
</P>
<P>
A second round and final round of voting on the draft law will
take place next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
