<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   DPRK: No UN Security Council Permanent Seat for Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- An editorial by the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea's(DPRK) newspaper Rodong Sinmun on
Saturday opposed Japan's request for a permanent seat in the UN
Security Council saying it is an "overweening" act.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government recently sent to UN representatives of
a number countries a resolution passed by its Diet (parliament),
asking them to back its bid to become a permanent member of the UN
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that Japan, as its donation to the UN comes
only next to that of the United States, should hold a permanent
seat in the council.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the UN seat should not be traded for money,
the editorial said that those to become permanent members should
receive due international support and trust.
</P>
<P>
As it has refused to expose and criticize the crimes it
committed in the past and repeatedly attempted to shirk its
responsibility, Japan has lost the trust of the Asian people and
people throughout the world, the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
To let such a Japan become a permanent member of the council
will be a challenge to justice and humiliation to the world
organization, it said.
</P>
<P>
Japan has been widely viewed as a potential threat to world
peace, to allow it to become a permanent member of the council
will also give it more freedom to launch wars of aggression
abroad, said the editorial.
</P>
<P>
If Japan wants to rebuild its image in the world, its
overwhelming task is to expose and criticize its past crimes, the
editorial noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
