<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Remove Illiteracy by 2006: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has taken
a massive program to remove illiteracy from the country by the
year 2006, the independent United News of Bangladesh (UNB)
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina while
inaugurating the centenary festival of a government high school in
Dhaka Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The program in this regard included establishing at least one
school in every one of (59,990) villages in the country, she told
the function.
</P>
<P>
She assured all possible help from the government, responding
to various demands of the school.
</P>
<P>
The government had given top priority to poverty alleviation,
the prime minister said in last March when addressing a meeting in
Dhaka. "It is an important task to remove illiteracy from the
society through developing human resources to alleviate poverty."
</P>
<P>
Illiteracy rate among people above the age of 15 now stands at
57.4 percent in this South Asian country with a population of 127
million. 
