<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chittagong Port in Severe Congestion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Severe congestion at Bangladesh's
biggest port, Chittagong, is forcing foreign cargo vessels to
overstay, causing those to incur huge demurrage, The Daily Star
reported Sunday quoting port officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Container ships and foodgrain-carrying vessels are the worst
sufferers, the officials said, adding that "five
foodgrain-carrying ships are now at the port jetties awaiting
unloading while three others are at the outer anchorage."
</P>
<P>
The congestion was caused by space problem at the port sheds to
accommodate containers and slow unloading of foodgrains by
laborers as the laborers were on a go-slow program following a
tussle with stevedores.
</P>
<P>
The ships are now required to overstay for 15 to 20 days
instead of five to six day in the past.
</P>
<P>
Eight container ships were waiting at the outer anchorage for
one week seeking berthing space at the port jetties while five
others were overstaying there.
</P>
<P>
The containers are unloaded very slowly due to space problem,
and over 13,000 containers are now dumped at the port sheds which
have a capacity to accommodate about 10,000 containers, port
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the importers are also slow in taking delivery of
container cargo, causing space problem, they added.
</P>
<P>
The port authorities are contemplating increasing charges to
force importers to take quick delivery of goods from port sheds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
