<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outlook for Second WTO Ministerial Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization (WTO)
will hold its second ministerial conference here on May 18-20 and
also celebrate the 50th anniversary of the operation of the
multilateral trading system on May 19.
</P>
<P>
Great achievements have been made by the organization since its
first ministerial conference in Singapore in December 1996 after
it succeeded the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) on
January 1, 1995.
</P>
<P>
WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero described 1997 as a golden
year, a year of harvest. He said that the agreements on basic
telecommunications, information technology and financial services
reached in 1997 have laid a sound foundation for further
development of world trade in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Fulfilling its tasks, WTO's major organ, the Dispute Settlement
Body (DSB), has handled more than 100 dispute cases, including the
Kodak-Fuji film dispute between the United States and Japan and
the Shrimp-Turtle dispute brought by India, Malaysia, Pakistan and
Thailand against the United States.
</P>
<P>
In the two cases, the United States has been considered by the
concerned members defeated though it has pledged to appeal and the
final verdicts are still pending. By these examples, WTO officials
want to tell the world that every member, strong or weak, big or
small, is equal in the dispute settlement mechanism.
</P>
<P>
However, one major challenge that the DSB has faced was the
case brought by the European Union (EU) in 1996 against the United
States. The EU insisted that the Cuban Liberty and Democratic
Solidarity Act of the United States, known as the Helms-Burton
act, was inconsistent with the U.S. obligations under the WTO
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Both major DSB proponents, the EU and the United States know
clearly that a settlement by the panel will be in no one's
interest. As concessions, the United States has postponed the
enforcement of the Helms-Burton act again and again. The EU, in
return, requested that the panel established on November 20, 1996
suspend its work.
</P>
<P>
Also since the Singapore conference, Congo, the Democratic
Republic of the Congo, Mongolia, Niger and Panama have become new
WTO members, raising the total to 132.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-one countries and regions including China and Russia
have been negotiating their accession to WTO.
</P>
<P>
The coming conference is expected to discuss the implementation
of the existing agreements, built-in agenda, future activities,
and the date and the place of the third ministerial conference.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 and early 1998, the WTO secretariat reviewed EU and
Japan's trade policies and said their tariffs were not at a
satisfactorily low level and there were even "tariff peaks" in
sectors like agriculture.
</P>
<P>
There is no rule for WTO to expel any of its members for their
insufficient implementation of WTO agreements. So, some of them
demand much more from the membership applicants than from
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Under the WTO agenda, members are to negotiate agriculture and
services by the end of 1999 and early 2000 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Many members from the developing countries believe that they
are encountering difficulties at home in implementing the existing
agreements and that it is unnecessary to have new negotiations
other than those on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
But members from the industrialized world want to see the
negotiations expanded to other areas. Some members led by the
United States wish to have an agreement on the electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
Most members have supported the WTO secretariat proposal for
holding the next ministerial conference in 1999, one year earlier
than scheduled, with the date and place to be decided yet.
</P>
<P>
No major breakthrough are expected at the coming ministerial
conference in Geneva, one seen just as playing a transitional role
to lay bricks for the new rounds of negotiations at the 1999
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Open More for Foreign Investment, Trade Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- China will strive to guide foreign
investment into different sectors and more areas, according to Shi
Guangsheng, minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
China welcomes more foreign investment in such areas as
agriculture, basic industries, high technology, infrastructure,
environmental protection and industries oriented to foreign trade,
Shi said during a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
China will make active efforts to guide foreign funds to
upgrade technology in its traditional industries and old
industrial centers, he said.
</P>
<P>
More and greater efforts will be made to develop
labor-intensive projects involving foreign investment in line with
industrial policies, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China will strictly prohibit those projects to the
detriment of national security, the public interest or the
environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
A number of certain sectors, including mineral resources, will
be opened with different emphasis and more capital from overseas
will be introduced into petrochemicals and construction, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will also further the opening-up step by step in the
service trade, including pilot projects of overseas investment in
tourism, water transportation, domestic commerce and foreign trade
as well as accounting, legal consulting services, and air
transportation and agent services.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China will open pilot projects in finance and
telecommunications and set up an efficient supervision system,
he said.
</P>
<P>
China also will take active measures to guide overseas
investment into central and western areas of China, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China will continue to support the development of
fund or tech-intensive industries and export-oriented industries
in the eastern parts of China, the minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
