<HEADLINE> Nuclear Tests Unsettle Bombay Stock Exchange Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The premier bourse in the
country, Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE), was rocked by the news of
nuclear tests, which witnessed heavy nervous offerings on
uncertainties in the market circles as to what extent the United
States would impose monetary sanctions on India.
</P>
<P>
As a result of panic selling the sensitive index plunged by
162.37 points to 3782.76 on May 13 on nervous selling by operators
in almost all Scripps. The weakening of the Indian rupee against
U.S. dollar had some negative impact on the market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index ended the week at 3849.80, sharply
lower by 172.40 points from the last weekend close of 4022.20. The
national index ended with a loss of 71.29 points at 1700.03 from
the previous weekend close of 1771.32. the BSE-200 was down at
384.49 and the U.S. dollar index at 159.05 from the previous close
of 401.36 and 167.98 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of business during the week was 43,918.2
million rupees (1,111.85 million dollars) as compared with
60,374.4 million rupees (1,528.47 million dollars) in the last
week.
</P>
<P>
The market would now move in a narrow band as the players are
expected to adopt wait-and-watch policy until the Union budget is
tabled later this month, operators said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
