<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Minister on China's Opening-up, Use of Foreign Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- China will continue its opening-up
efforts and further improve the use of foreign capital for its
economic development, said Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC) Shi Guangsheng in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
The use of overseas funds -- in the form of direct investment,
foreign loans or capital raised through stock markets -- has
steadily increased in the past two decades, Shi said, adding that
the move played a role in the speedy, sustained and healthy growth
of China's economy.
</P>
<P>
He said China has accumulated experience in the field and that
some problems still exist. "The Chinese government attaches
importance to these problems and will find solutions to them," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Shi said China will utilize overseas capital in active and
rational ways to meet the increasing demand of China's economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
"We will make efforts to keep the current overseas investment
scale to ensure that China stays atop developing countries in
terms of direct investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
To meet the goal, according to Shi, China will further optimize
the industrial structure for foreign investment, make more fields
accessible to overseas investors, improve the geological location
of foreign capital, attract capital through multiple channels,
introduce and direct investment from multinational corporations,
properly manage the existing ventures with overseas capital,
further improve the investment environment and raise capital from
overseas stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Shi cited direct investment still as the focus of China's
efforts. To optimize overall investment structure, China will
continue adopting tariff-free and value-added-tax-free treatments
for the technologies or projects in the categories encouraged or
supported by the state for overseas investors, he said. "China is
to formulate more incentive policies for overseas investors into
its central and western regions."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Shi noted, China will appropriately borrow and make
better use of foreign loans. It will thus far strictly control its
foreign debt, improve the management of overseas borrowing,
improve the efficiency of using foreign loans, and set up a
borrow-use-return mechanism for users.
</P>
<P>
To further improve the work, Shi urged a strengthening of the
leadership in the field and enhancing the relevant legal
construction. "We hope to use about three years's time to build up
a comprehensive legal system on the use of overseas investment,"
Shi said.
</P>
<P>
According to Shi, China will step up its pace in promulgating
anti-trust laws, and revising the current law against unfair
competitions, and do a still better job in protecting intellectual
property rights better still, and training a contingent of
qualified staff members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
