<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urged to Continue Improving Investment Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- China must step up efforts to
improve its investment climate to prevent a decline in foreign
capital inflow, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
A senior researcher is quoted as saying that the nation's
picture of foreign investment will be gloomy if no action is
taken, according to Ma Yu, director of the department of foreign
capital with the Chinese Academy of International Trade and
Economic Co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Foreign capital into China has witnessed an extraordinary surge
over the past two decades, with rapid market expansion and high
returns making up for various restrictions on foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign investors have begun to worry about various
elements detrimental to their interests as economic growth
decelerates and investment returns taper off.
</P>
<P>
The fluctuation of macro-control policies, such as the
resumption of tariff on imported capital goods of foreign
investors, has made it hard for foreign investors to calculate
their investment costs and returns.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the present foreign investment administration
system also limits the effectiveness of foreign investment. For
example, when investment in an individual project exceeds US 30
million US dollars, investors have to submit their feasibility
studies and contracts to central governmental bodies for
examination and approval. The approval procedures usually last
several months, which may put the investors at a serious
disadvantage in view of the rapid changes occurring in the market.
</P>
<P>
Ma suggested government agencies only examine and approve
projects in the sectors where foreign investment should be
restricted.
</P>
<P>
This proposal is in line with the country's economic reforms,
which aim to allow market forces to play the leading role in
microeconomic sectors, the researcher said.
</P>
<P>
Ma also said the problem of random fees charged by local
governments might be alleviated by the ongoing governmental
restructuring, though the final solution still lies with less
government interference and a sound legal system.
</P>
<P>
The attraction of China's huge market may lose its appeal as
the market becomes more and more open with the lowering of tariff
and non-tariff barriers, said Ma.
</P>
<P>
China has been the world's second largest recipient of foreign
capital for five years running. However, the rapid momentum of
foreign capital inflow slowed down last year, when actual foreign
investment rose only 8.5 percent over 1996 and contracted amount
plunged 29.3 percent from the figure for the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
