<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICAO to Fully Launch New Air Navigation System by 2010 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Civil
Aviation Organization (ICAO) has decided that a new air traffic
guiding system would be put into complete use as from 2010.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at ICAO's five-day World Conference,
which ended here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The milestone system -- Communication, Navigation, and
Surveillance/Air Traffic Management (CNS/ATM) would allow the
control of air navigation via satellite in transoceanic
transportation and in remote areas instead of depending on the
radar signals sent from ground stations presently.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the new system would also permit information to be
sent directly by satellites to computers aboard.
</P>
<P>
ICAO Council President Assad Kotiate said the new system would
make it possible for aircraft to fly in a more straight direction
at the best altitude, which means fuel economy and less air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
The conference, attended by 700 representatives from 123
countries and 27 international organizations, also discussed
issues related to air traffic new technologies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
