<HEADLINE> Ministry to Tighten Control on Port Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The layout of ports in China has
been basically rational. Port construction should be shifted
towards technical renovation, increase in handling capacity and
enhancement of viability, rather than launching new projects.
</P>
<P>
Huang Zhendong, minister of communications, was quoted by
today's China Daily" as saying that the establishment of special
berths by cargo owners must be subject to overall State planning.
</P>
<P>
Massive port construction along China's coastline and major
rivers is creating duplication and waste of resources, despite
warnings to investors from the ministry.
</P>
<P>
In some areas, uncontrolled port construction has led to
cut-throat competition among the operators and local governments,
who are vying to under-cut each other to grab cargo sources.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province, for instance, had thought to position
Shenzhen as its container shipping center, but Guangzhou,
Zhanjiang, and Zhuhai have all pushed for similar projects.
</P>
<P>
China has 485 deep-water coastal docks with handling capacity
surpassing 780 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Communications, having survived the government
restructuring, plans to strengthen macro-management of port
building by identifying the functions of existing ports and
tightening control on approval of berth projects.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the move will cut across the vested interests
of ministries, local governments and large State-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, in the long run, this will benefit the long-term
sustained development of the ports and better serve economic
growth, Minister Huang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
