<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Preparations for Clinton's Visit in Full Swing (2) by Peng Shujie, Liu Yunfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. dignitaries and ranking officials were accorded courteous
reception during their trips in Beijing, and the two sides have
exchanged views on issues related to Clinton's coming visit.
</P>
<P>
Albright noted that the U.S. is seeking to build "a more
constructive relationship with China through strategic dialogue"
despite differences between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The opening of a hot line has made it possible for leaders of
the White House and Zhongnanhai to contact each other "rapidly,
directly and candidly" whenever they feel it is necessary, said
Albright after she signed the agreement with Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary of State for East Asia and Pacific Affairs
Stanley Roth also said in Washington early this week that Clinton's
China trip is intended to increase strategic dialogue between the
United States and China.
</P>
<P>
Together with their meeting while attending the fifth informal
leadership meeting of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
in Vancouver, Canada, in November last year, the two presidents
will have met each other three times within eight months. Also,
they have exchanged two letters during this period of time.
</P>
<P>
This itself is a good demonstration of the fact that a sound
China-U.S. relationship and a strategic partnership are in the
fundamental interests of the two countries, local observers said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they believe that the two sides are likely to reach
more common understanding with existing mutually beneficial
cooperation bolstered through Clinton's upcoming visit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
