<HEADLINE> Talks Between Microsoft, Government Break Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The negotiations between Microsoft
Corp., the world's most powerful software maker, and government
lawyers aimed at averting antitrust lawsuits broke up Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sources reaching here indicated that the Justice Department and
at least 20 states would be back to collision with Microsoft,
which is very eager to put its new operating system Windows 98 to
computer makers and retailers in time.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department said talks, which broke up at midday,
were not expected to resume. The government and the states were
expected to file two separate but similar federal antitrust
lawsuits Monday morning in U.S. District Court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Federal lawyers and state attorneys general contend that
Microsoft illegally used its market power to assert pressure on
its competitors, by binding its Internet browser in its operating
systems.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft accused the government of making "unreasonable
demands" and agreed negotiations were at an impasse.
</P>
<P>
An official with one of the state attorneys general said only
that talks broke down because Microsoft made no "substantial
offers" to keep them moving forward.
</P>
<P>
The company originally planned to ship to computer makers the
latest upgrade to its flagship software Windows 98 Friday. But
when the government and the 20 states threatened to file antitrust
lawsuits against it Thursday, it offered to delay its shipment in
order to have more talks with the government which resumed Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
