<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-8 Leaders Declare War on International Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from the Group of Eight
(G-8) countries expressed here Saturday their strong determination
to make joint efforts in fighting against various kinds of
international crime.
</P>
<P>
G-8 leaders, meeting in Birmingham for their annual summit,
said in a statement that globalization has been accompanied by a
dramatic increase in transnational crime, including drug
trafficking, smuggling of human beings, money laundering and the
abuse of the new technologies.
</P>
<P>
"Such crimes pose not only a threat to our own citizens and
their communities, but also a global one which can undermine the
economic basis of societies through the investment of illegal
money," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders from the United States, Germany, France, Italy,
Canada, Japan, Britain and Russia stressed that international
cooperation is indispensable in fighting such transnational
crimes.
</P>
<P>
As further actions to tackle this threat, the participants
pledged to "fully support efforts to negotiate within the next two
years an effective United Nations convention against international
crime."
</P>
<P>
They also vowed to take some concrete actions in cracking down
on high tech crime, money laundering, all forms of tracking of
human beings and illegal manufacturing and trafficking of
firearms.
</P>
<P>
On the transnational drug trafficking, the document noted that
the G-8 countries are committed to partnership and shared
responsibility in the international community to combat illicit
drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
