<DOCNO> XIE19980517.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-8 Reaffirms Initiative on Debt Relief for HIPC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- All G-8 leaders reaffirmed here
Saturday that they are all committed to helping heavily indebted
poor countries free themselves from the burden of their
unsustainable debts.
</P>
<P>
It has been two years when the G-7 leaders initiated in Lyon
the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) designed to ensure a
sustainable exit from their debt burden for all the most affected
countries.
</P>
<P>
Over the last three years, official creditors have forgiven in
favor of the poorest countries 8 billion U.S. dollars with more
than 5 billion U.S. dollars of that relief going to Africa.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the G-8 heads of state and government, British
Secretary of State for International Development Clare Short said,
"We will work with the others concerned to ensure that all
eligible countries get the relief they need to secure a lasting
exit from their debt problems."
</P>
<P>
So far six countries have qualified for debt relief from the
HIPC initiative totaling around 5.7 billion U.S. dollars. Among
those six countries, Uganda has been the first to complete the
process, recently receiving additional debt relief of nearly 650
million U.S. dollars, according to Short.
</P>
<P>
In addition to these countries, Short said, "Two more countries
have already benefited from preliminary positive indications
regarding their possible eligibility under the HIPC initiative."
</P>
<P>
In his conclusion, Short said the G-8 leaders' ambition "is to
ensure the speedy and determined implementation of the initiative
and encourage all eligible countries to take the policy measures
needed to embark on the process as soon as possible, so that all
can be in the process by the year 2000." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
